i## Understanding Open5GS Components		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen5GS, as its name suggests, is primarily a software that implements		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ia 5G core network (as well as a LTE core network). Since the core		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork protocols and structure in the 5G era are significantly		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idifferent from the 4G era, especially for standalone 5G SA networks,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOpen5GS can roughly be seen as a set of LTE/5G NSA core network		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isoftware, plus a set of 5G SA core network software, with a small		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iportion of components shared between them.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe LTE/5G NSA part of Open5GS consists of the following components:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- MME - Mobility Management Entity		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- HSS - Home Subscriber Server		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- PCRF - Policy and Charging Rules Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- SGWC - Serving Gateway Control Plane		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- SGWU - Serving Gateway User Plane		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- SMF - Session Management Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - SMF itself is a 5G core network component, but Open5GS SMF also		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    implements the Packet Gateway Control Plane in the 4G core network		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    structure.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- UPF - User Plane Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - UPF itself is a 5G core network component, but Open5GS UPF also		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    implements the Packet Gateway User Plane in the 4G core network		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    structure.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- SCP -		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Secure, Contain, Protect		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Service Communication Proxy		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - SCP itself is a 5G core network component, but SMF depends on it.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- NRF - NF Repository Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - NRF itself is a 5G core network component, but SCP depends on it.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAnd the 5G SA part consists of the following components:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- NRF - NF Repository Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- SCP - Service Communication Proxy		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- SEPP - Security Edge Protection Proxy		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- AMF - Access and Mobility Management Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- SMF - Session Management Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- UPF - User Plane Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- AUSF - Authentication Server Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- UDM - Unified Data Management		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- UDR - Unified Data Repository		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- PCF - Policy and Charging Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- NSSF - Network Slice Selection Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- BSF - Binding Support Function		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThese components communicate with each other in the following		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istructure:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
IOpen5GS Component Architecture Diagram	/usr/uploads/202507/Open5GS_CUPS-01.jpg	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i(Image source:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hOpen5GS official documentation	URL:https://open5gs.org/open5gs/docs/guide/01-quickstart/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe communication between various components of the 4G/5G core network		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iuses the standardized		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hDiameter protocol	URL:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diameter_(protocol)	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i, which is based on TCP or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hSCTP	URL:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stream_Control_Transmission_Protocol	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprotocol, exchanging data between various components of the 4G/5G core		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inetwork. This also means that hardware and software from different		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivendors, as long as they support the Diameter protocol, can join the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isame core network and jointly provide services to mobile users.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, in this post, I will only use Open5GS components, and will		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
